\pard\f0\fs28  A misunderstood species whose area is not yet clear because of confusion with {\b 6}, {\b 9}, {\b 11} and {\b 13}. Especially uncertain is the status of plants from S. Germany (whence {\i P. tuberosa} was described) which have been found to have 2n = 18; similar plants seem to occur in E. France and C. Germany.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 11. P. longifolia} (Bast.) Boreau, {\i Fl. Centre Fr}. ed. 3, {\b 2}: 460 (1857) ({\i P. vulgaris} Mérat pro parte, {\i P. angustifolia }auct., non L.). Summer leaves up to 50 × 6 cm, narrowly lanceolate, very gradually narrowed to the base, usually with white spots, rarely (especially in the far west) unspotted or with faint green spots; the upper surface with more or less equal setae and few glands, the lower surface with unequal setae and more glandular. Inflorescence remaining dense throughout the flowering period, with long setae and a few long glandular hairs. Corolla violet to blue-violet (often almost blue in the far west); tube glabrous inside below the ring of hairs. Nutlets 4 × 3 mm. 2n = 14. •{\i  W. Europe, northwards to England.} Br Ga Hs Lu.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  In W. & C. France, unspotted blue-flowered plants with 2n = 14 are found; they have usually been confused with {\b 12}. Special taxonomic treatment may be necessary.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 12. P. angustifolia} L., {\i Sp. Pl}. 135 (1753) ({\i P. azurea} Besser, {\i P. angustifolia} subsp.{\i  azurea} (Besser) Gams). Summer leaves up to 40 × 5 cm, narrowly lanceolate, very gradually narrowed to the base, unspotted, with equal setae, more or less eglandular. Cauline leaves narrowly lanceolate, sessile, with narrow base. Inflorescence with setae and scattered glands. Calyx in fruit very slender and short. Corolla bright blue; tube glabrous inside below the ring of hairs. Nutlets 4·5 × 3·5 mm. 2n = 14.{\i  N.E., E. & E.C. Europe; isolated stations in W.C. Europe and the S.W. Alps.} Au ?Bu Cz Da Ga Ge Hu It ?Ju Po Rs (B, C, W, E) Su.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Many records of this species from S.E. Europe are of narrow leaved variants of{\b  6}; records from the E. Alps and neighbouring territory to the south-east are referable to {\b 13}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 13. P. visianii} Degen & Lengyel in Degen,{\i  Fl. Veleb. }{\b 2}: 569 (1937) ({\i P. media} Host pro parte,{\i  P. angustifolia} auct., non L.). Like {\b 12} but summer leaves up to 30 × 6 cm, unspotted or rarely with indistinct green spots, with unequal setae and scattered glands; inflorescence hispid and glandular; fruiting calyx stout; corolla deep blue-violet to blue; nutlets 3·5 × 3 mm. 2n = 20. •{\i  C. & E. Alps, mountains of N.W. Jugoslavia.} Au ?Ga He It Ju.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 14. P. kerneri} Wettst.,{\i  Yerh. Zool.-Bot. Ges. Wien} {\b 38}: 559 (1888). Summer leaves up to 60 × 10 cm, lanceolate, very gradually narrowed to the base, thick, coriaceous, usually with distinct white spots, rarely more or less unspotted, with stiff setae and scattered short glands. Cauline leaves lanceolate, sessile, with broad base. Corolla bright blue, tube glabrous inside below the ring of hairs. Nutlets 5 × 3 mm. 2n = 26.{\i  N.E. Alps.} Au.
\par

